1- Why each element was added

HAProxy (load balancer) — added to distribute incoming traffic across both servers so no single server is overwhelmed. It also provides a single public entry point (one IP) while hiding the backend topology.
2 servers — redundancy. If one server goes down, the other keeps serving traffic. It also allows horizontal scaling.
Nginx on each server — each server needs its own web server to receive the requests forwarded by HAProxy, serve static files, and proxy dynamic requests to the local app server.
App server + codebase on each — the application logic runs independently on each server; both copies are identical so either can handle any request.
MySQL Primary + Replica — the database is split so writes are handled by one node (Primary) while reads can be offloaded to the Replica, improving performance and providing a data backup.

2- Load balancer specifics

Algorithm: Round Robin — HAProxy sends request 1 to Server 1, request 2 to Server 2, request 3 to Server 1, and so on in rotation. Each server gets an equal share of traffic. It works well when servers have similar capacity and request costs.
Active-Active vs Active-Passive:

Active-Active (what we have) — both servers are live and handling traffic simultaneously. HAProxy distributes load between them. Full capacity is used at all times.
Active-Passive — one server handles all traffic; the second sits idle as a hot standby. It only takes over if the active server fails. Wastes capacity but simpler to reason about consistency.


3- Primary-Replica (Master-Slave) how it works

The Primary receives all write operations (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE) from the app. Every write is recorded in a binary log (binlog). The Replica connects to the Primary, reads that binlog, and replays each operation on its own copy of the data — keeping itself in sync asynchronously.
From the application's perspective:

Primary node — the app sends all write queries here. It is the authoritative source of truth.
Replica node — the app can send read-only queries (SELECT) here to reduce load on the Primary. The Replica cannot accept writes from the application — doing so would break replication sync.


4- Issues with this infrastructure

SPOF — HAProxy itself is a single point of failure: if it goes down, neither server is reachable even though they're both healthy. The Primary database is also a SPOF — if it crashes, all write operations fail until it's restored.
Security — no firewall means every port on every server is exposed to the public internet. No HTTPS means all traffic (including passwords and session tokens) flows in plaintext and can be intercepted.
No monitoring — there is no visibility into server health, resource usage, error rates, or query performance. Problems are only discovered after users report them, making incident response slow and reactive.
